<br>
Rotations are for sharing mobs you could otherwise kill at your whim.<br>
<br>
Rotations 'tell' my guild what we can or cant kill, and when.<br>
<br>
Rotations are a player-made agreement, they are not verant enforced (except when foul play is introduced, like ks/train).<br>
<br>
So:  I (and my guild) *A G R E E* to hold back and *N O T* kill mobs that we otherwise could, within specefic agreements *to those involved*.  When a new party comes in and *Disrupts* this agreement for us (or other parties involved in this agreement), we are not inclined to *respect* the protection you enjoy on other artificially *protected mobs*.<br>
<br>
It's not a case of saying 'you cant kill this mob', its a case of 'if you cannot use judgement, discipline and respect to try to follow preset rules of preset agreements that have been hashed out to ensure fairness for all involved, then what drives those affected by your selfish actions to respect the protection of mobs you enjoy by our agreement to not kill them?'<br>
<br>
translated to principally:<br>
<br>
rotations are established to be fair.  if you break a part of a rotation, you are basically claiming you have no regard for them, and such invalidate your other rotations.<br>
<br>
remember: &quot;Rotations are a player-made agreement, they are not verant enforced (except when foul play is introduced, like ks/train).&quot;<br>
<br>
which means there is no guarantee to be admited to these rotations, admittance is given through set criteria, and the 'membership' is extended in good faith that you will try to maintain integrity throughout all the aspects of all the rotations. <p><a href="http://www.drow.org/eq/roster/viewprofile.php?name=Emil">Emil Sinclair</a><br>
<a href="http://www.drow.org/news.shtml">BotS</a>
